, 
<taxonomicNameLabel>n. s.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="158" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="158" type="mainText">Worker. - Length lines. Black, smooth and shining, covered with fine, short, pale, glittering pubescence, interspersed with scattered, erect, long, pale hairs; the upper surface of the thorax flattened, having the sides sharp and angulated; the mandibles rufo-testaceous; the claws rufo-piceous, the calcaria pale testaceous; the metathorax slightly curved above, from the base to the apex.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="158" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="158" type="mainText">
This species is from Brazil. I believe this insect would fall into the genus Condijlodon of Lund. I have been unable to detect anything beyond specific differences between that genus and 
<taxonomicName authority="Guérin-Ménéville, 1844" authorityName="Guérin-Ménéville" authorityYear="1844" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pseudomyrma</taxonomicName>
, as characterized by M. Guerin. In my own Collection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
